    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Hemmant sits in Brisbane's eastern corridor, east of Tingalpa and adjacent to Lytton and Wynnum West, occupying low-lying land between the Gateway Motorway and Moreton Bay. It is a suburb of larger blocks and older housing stock, with a mix of original post-war homes, acreage-style properties and some newer infill development. The suburb is not a typical target for buyers who prioritise inner-city access above all else, but it consistently attracts buyers who want land, space and a quieter residential character that is becoming increasingly rare at accessible price points in the broader eastern corridor.</p>

      <p>The Hemmant market rewards sellers who understand its specific buyer profile. Buyers here are making a deliberate choice: they have assessed the trade-off between city proximity and land size, and they have decided in favour of space. Marketing that speaks to that choice, rather than trying to position Hemmant as something it is not, will reach the right buyers faster and generate stronger results.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Hemmant</h2>
      <p>Tradies, small business owners and families seeking a large block at an accessible price are the most consistent buyer segment in Hemmant. The suburb's zoning and block sizes also attract buyers interested in keeping animals, operating a home-based business or storing boats and work vehicles, which is a distinct buyer segment not present in most inner-east suburbs. First home buyers entering the detached home market with a preference for space over proximity are also active. The investor segment is present but not dominant: Hemmant's rental market is thinner than inner suburbs and the yield story is less compelling at current prices.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Hemmant</h2>
      <p>Land size is the primary value driver, more so than in almost any other suburb in the eastern corridor. A large, flat and usable block in Hemmant is the asset buyers are specifically seeking, and the internal condition of the home is secondary to the land attributes for many buyers in this market. Properties with water access or proximity to the creek and bay system attract a premium from boating and outdoor lifestyle buyers. The condition and usability of any sheds, garages or secondary structures are factors that buyers in Hemmant assess carefully, because many are purchasing specifically for those attributes.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing for sale</h2>
      <p>Pre-sale preparation in Hemmant should focus on presenting the land and its usability as clearly as possible. Tidy the yard, ensure any sheds or outbuildings are accessible and presentable, and address any safety or compliance issues with fencing or structures before listing. The internal presentation of the home remains important, but buyers here are spending as much time inspecting the land and outbuildings as they are the interior. If the property has features that appeal to specific buyer segments, such as a large hardstand, a boat ramp or a powered shed, these should be prominently featured in the marketing rather than treated as incidental details.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Campaign approach</h2>
      <p>Private treaty with a clearly stated price works well in Hemmant, because the buyer pool is practical and price-driven. Buyers in this market want to assess whether the asking price is fair relative to recent comparable sales before they invest time in an inspection. Auction is less commonly effective in Hemmant given the more specific buyer profile: the pool of buyers who will compete at auction for a large eastern corridor block is smaller than in inner suburbs, and the auction format can create unnecessary friction. The most important element of any Hemmant campaign is ensuring the marketing reaches the specific buyer segments that value what the property offers, rather than broadcasting broadly and hoping the right buyer finds it.</p>


      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Hemmant</h2>
      <p>Hemmant's residential market is quieter and more seasonal than the inner eastern suburbs. Spring (September to November) is the primary selling window, generating the highest buyer volumes for the family homes that dominate the suburb's housing stock. The suburb sits in Brisbane's eastern corridor, and buyers here are often comparing Hemmant against Murarrie, Tingalpa, and Wynnum West — looking for value at accessible price points with Gateway Motorway access. The post-Christmas January-February period also produces some activity from buyers who resolved relocation decisions over the holiday period. Hemmant benefits from periodic investor activity tied to rental yield demand in Brisbane's east, and those buyers tend to be more year-round in their timing than owner-occupier families.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Hemmant</h2>
      <p>Hemmant homes typically spend 35 to 50 days on market. The buyer pool is smaller than inner-city suburbs, which means finding the right buyer takes more time even for well-presented and correctly priced stock. Gateway Motorway access is a consistent draw for buyers working at the port or the airport precinct, and those buyers are present throughout the year as employment decisions drive their moves independently of seasonal patterns. Properties with larger blocks and space for sheds, boats, or trade vehicles have a specific buyer appeal that is not as time-sensitive as the family home market. Hemmant is not a suburb where overpricing can be absorbed by deep buyer competition — stock that is mispriced relative to Murarrie and Tingalpa comparables stalls noticeably.</p>

